ce:section.ce:para:
Optimization and property calculations for the adsorption of ADO on GG were done using the Gaussian 16 and GaussView version 6 at the B3LYP/6-31G* level [52,53]. Five graphene based carriers (Fig. 1
                     ), including pristine graphene (coronene: GG), B/N substituted graphenes (B/N at para positions: GBB/GNN; B and N at para/ortho; GBNP/GBNO) at the middle ring were designed here for adsorption of the ADO molecule. The default setting was used for the convergence criteria regarding SCF and optimization procedure. Optimized structures, FMOs and MEP plots of ADO are shown in Fig. 2
                     . After identical-level hessian simulations were performed to validate the real minima in each case. The stability of the complexes was evaluated using the binding energy. The GaussSum application was used to acquire DOS results [54]. The topological studies were by Multiwfn [55] and visualization by VMD software [56].

The stability of the ADO adsorbed complexes was investigated by binding energies (ΔEb). Magnitudes of the binding energy values of complexes (Table 1
                        ), follow the order GNN (−284.13 kcal mol−1) > GBNP (−255.41 kcal mol−1) > GBNO (−254.91 kcal mol−1) > GBB (−261.78 kcal mol−1) > GG (−6.02 kcal mol−1). The series demonstrate that the magnitude of ΔEb between ADO and identical N-doped atoms in parallel position in the GG is bigger than that between other systems and GG adsorption gives a lowest value. To compare the practicality of the ADO adsorption process on coronene, the thermodynamic parameters are determined (Table 2
                        ). The order of ΔH values for the ADO-coronene are negative and is as: GNN (−284.61 kcal mol−1) > GBB (−261.79 kcal mol−1) > GBNP (−256.09 kcal mol−1) > GBNO (−255.56 kcal mol−1) > GG (−5.18 kcal mol−1). All the ΔS values are negative, means a spontaneous process. The ΔG values are negative for doped systems indicating that the ADO adsorption on nanosurfaces occurs spontaneously while for GG system, the value is less and positive. On the other hand, compared to pristine and other systems, the ΔGad values for ADO adsorption on the same substitution at para locations on centre of the nanosystem are higher [61, 62]. The exothermic nature of ADO adsorption on nanocarrier surfaces is further suggested by the negative value of ΔHad 
                        [63].
